<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,492,610]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
This is the most northerly of the series, from the 
<collectingCountry box="[750,828,493,516]" name="Yemen" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Yemen</collectingCountry>
highlands, and is distinguished by the orange±brown abdominal sterna and legs and by the predominantly yellow scaling on the abdominal terga. A series of specimens from 
<collectingCountry name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
, discussed below, may also belong to this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="140" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,649,952]" box="[92,199,649,672]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis box="[92,199,649,672]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,649,952]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
Antenna with scape and pedicel red; second ¯agellomere very short, little longer than wide. Face orange and with a conspicuous tuft of black hair at the apex. Legs brown with ochreous scales. Body with sterna usually orange±brown, sometimes blackened at their bases; hair and scales predominantly yellow and white, a distinct band of black scales present on t2 only, black hairs present at sides of abdominal terga only. Wing with cell r broadly open, membrane tinged brownish and darker 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[410,420,851,875]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">5</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,649,952]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
borders to veins very feint, spots distinct and darker. Male genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="GREATHEAD, D. J." pageId="15" pageNumber="140" pagination="337" refId="ref11525" refString="GREATHEAD, D. J., 1980 a, Insects of Saudi Arabia. Diptera: Fam. Bombyliidae, Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 2, 291 ± 337." type="journal article" year="1980">Greathead, 1980a</bibRefCitation>
: ®gure 29) very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[468,607,897,921]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicosta">
<emphasis box="[468,607,897,921]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">E. luteicosta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Spermatheca as 
<taxonomicName box="[811,950,897,921]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicosta">
<emphasis box="[811,950,897,921]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">E. luteicosta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Length of body, 
<quantity box="[197,313,928,952]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" unit="mm" value="13.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="13.0">13±14 mm</quantity>
; of wing, 
<quantity box="[433,549,928,952]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" unit="mm" value="13.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="13.0">13±14 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,991,1202]" box="[92,224,991,1015]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis box="[92,224,991,1015]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,991,1202]" box="[132,218,1023,1046]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
<collectingCountry box="[132,214,1023,1046]" name="Yemen" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Yemen</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[92,1047,991,1202]" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">
A series of specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[438,588,1054,1078]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[606,654,1054,1078]" country="Saudi Arabia" name="'Asir" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">Asir</collectingRegion>
highlands) are smaller, 
<quantity box="[923,1039,1054,1078]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="12.0">12±13 mm</quantity>
, have a darker cuticle with legs and abdominal sterna blackish, predominantly white rather than yellow scales and wing pattern darker like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaennicke" authorityYear="1867" box="[748,855,1116,1140]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="busiris">
<emphasis box="[748,855,1116,1140]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">E. busiris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Since the male genitalia are identical with those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greathead" authorityYear="1980" box="[531,628,1148,1171]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Exoprosopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiris">
<emphasis box="[531,628,1148,1171]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="140">E. asiris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they, almost certainly, represent a distinct population of the same species.
</paragraph>
